## 🏆 Frequency Count Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) return false;
        int[] count = new int[26];
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            count[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            count[t.charAt(i) - 'a']--;
        }
        for (int c : count) {
            if (c != 0) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Length Check

- If lengths differ → immediately return false
- Anagrams must have same number of characters

### 2️⃣ Frequency Array

- `int[26]` covers all lowercase English letters
- Index 0 = 'a', Index 25 = 'z'

### 3️⃣ Count Up and Down

- Increment for each char in `s`
- Decrement for each char in `t`
- If they're anagrams, everything cancels to 0

### 4️⃣ Validate Counts

- If any count ≠ 0 → different frequencies → not anagram
- All zeros → valid anagram

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1) -fixed 26 characters

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use a frequency array of size 26 -increment for s, decrement for t, and check all zeros. O(n) time, O(1) space.'

## 🏆 Stack Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isValid(String s) {
        Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (c == '(') stack.push(')');
            else if (c == '{') stack.push('}');
            else if (c == '[') stack.push(']');
            else if (stack.isEmpty() || stack.pop() != c) return false;
        }
        return stack.isEmpty();
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Push Expected Close

- For '(' push ')'
- For '{' push '}'
- For '[' push ']'
- Stores what we EXPECT to see next

### 2️⃣ Compare on Close Bracket

- If stack is empty → no matching open bracket
- Pop and compare → if mismatch, invalid

### 3️⃣ Final Check

- Stack must be empty at end
- Non-empty stack = unmatched open brackets remain

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(n)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I push the expected closing bracket for each open bracket, then pop and compare when I see a close -if stack is empty at end, it's valid.'

## 🏆 Two Pointer Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPalindrome(String s) {
        int left = 0, right = s.length() - 1;
        while (left < right) {
            while (left < right && !Character.isLetterOrDigit(s.charAt(left))) left++;
            while (left < right && !Character.isLetterOrDigit(s.charAt(right))) right--;
            if (Character.toLowerCase(s.charAt(left)) != Character.toLowerCase(s.charAt(right))) return false;
            left++;
            right--;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Initialize Pointers

- `left` starts at index 0
- `right` starts at last index
- Move toward each other

### 2️⃣ Skip Non-Alphanumeric

- Skip spaces, punctuation from both sides
- Only compare valid characters

### 3️⃣ Case-Insensitive Compare

- Convert both to lowercase before comparing
- If mismatch → not a palindrome

### 4️⃣ Converge

- Move both pointers inward after each match
- Loop ends when pointers meet → palindrome confirmed

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use two pointers from both ends, skip non-alphanumeric characters, compare lowercase -O(n) time with O(1) space.'

## 🏆 Sliding Window + HashSet Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        Set<Character> set = new HashSet<>();
        int left = 0, maxLen = 0;
        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            while (set.contains(s.charAt(right))) {
                set.remove(s.charAt(left));
                left++;
            }
            set.add(s.charAt(right));
            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
        }
        return maxLen;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ HashSet as Window Tracker

- Stores all unique characters in current window
- Enables O(1) duplicate detection

### 2️⃣ Expand Right Pointer

- Add one new character each iteration
- Grows the window to explore longer substrings

### 3️⃣ Shrink Left on Duplicate

- If new char already in set → shrink from left
- Remove chars until duplicate is gone
- Maintains invariant: no repeats in window

### 4️⃣ Track Maximum

- Window size = `right - left + 1`
- Update maxLen after each valid expansion

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n) -each char added/removed at most once
- Space: O(min(n, 26)) -bounded by charset

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use a sliding window with a HashSet -expand right to grow, shrink left to fix duplicates, track max window size. O(n) time.'

## 🏆 Sliding Window + Frequency Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int characterReplacement(String s, int k) {
        int[] count = new int[26];
        int left = 0, maxFreq = 0, maxLen = 0;
        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            count[s.charAt(right) - 'A']++;
            maxFreq = Math.max(maxFreq, count[s.charAt(right) - 'A']);
            while ((right - left + 1) - maxFreq > k) {
                count[s.charAt(left) - 'A']--;
                left++;
            }
            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
        }
        return maxLen;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Frequency Array

- `int[26]` tracks count of each char in current window
- Updates as window expands/shrinks

### 2️⃣ Track Max Frequency

- `maxFreq` = count of most common char in window
- The dominant character we'll keep

### 3️⃣ Validity Check

- Characters to replace = `window_size - maxFreq`
- If replacements needed > k → shrink window from left

### 4️⃣ Why maxFreq Never Decreases

- We only care about larger windows than current best
- A larger window needs at least as high maxFreq
- So it's safe to never decrement maxFreq

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1) -fixed 26 characters

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use a sliding window where the validity condition is that characters to replace (window_size - maxFreq) must not exceed k. O(n) time, O(1) space.'

## 🏆 Sort as Key Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public List<List<String>> groupAnagrams(String[] strs) {
        Map<String, List<String>> map = new HashMap<>();
        for (String s : strs) {
            char[] chars = s.toCharArray();
            Arrays.sort(chars);
            String key = new String(chars);
            map.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(s);
        }
        return new ArrayList<>(map.values());
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ HashMap for Grouping

- Key → sorted version of the string
- Value → list of original strings that sort to this key

### 2️⃣ Sort Each String

- Convert to char array and sort
- "eat" → "aet", "tea" → "aet", "ate" → "aet"
- All anagrams produce the same sorted form

### 3️⃣ Group by Key

- `computeIfAbsent` creates list if key not present
- Add original string to its group

### 4️⃣ Return All Groups

- `map.values()` gives all grouped lists
- Wrap in ArrayList for the return type

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n × k log k) -n strings, k = max length
- Space: O(n × k)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I sort each string to create a canonical key -all anagrams sort identically -then group them in a HashMap. O(n × k log k) time.'

## 🏆 Expand Around Center Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String longestPalindrome(String s) {
        int start = 0, maxLen = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            int len1 = expand(s, i, i);     // odd length
            int len2 = expand(s, i, i + 1); // even length
            int len = Math.max(len1, len2);
            if (len > maxLen) {
                maxLen = len;
                start = i - (len - 1) / 2;
            }
        }
        return s.substring(start, start + maxLen);
    }

    private int expand(String s, int left, int right) {
        while (left >= 0 && right < s.length() && s.charAt(left) == s.charAt(right)) {
            left--;
            right++;
        }
        return right - left - 1;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Try Every Center

- Each character is a potential center (odd palindromes)
- Each gap between chars is a potential center (even palindromes)
- Total: 2n - 1 centers

### 2️⃣ Expand Outward

- From center, move left and right outward
- Continue while chars match
- Stop at first mismatch

### 3️⃣ Track Longest

- Compare odd and even lengths from each center
- Update start index and maxLen if longer found

### 4️⃣ Calculate Start Index

- `start = i - (len - 1) / 2`
- Works for both odd and even length palindromes

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n²)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I expand around each of the 2n-1 possible centers (each char and each gap), tracking the longest palindrome found. O(n²) time, O(1) space.'

## 🏆 Expand Around Center (Count)

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int countSubstrings(String s) {
        int count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            count += expand(s, i, i);     // odd
            count += expand(s, i, i + 1); // even
        }
        return count;
    }

    private int expand(String s, int left, int right) {
        int count = 0;
        while (left >= 0 && right < s.length() && s.charAt(left) == s.charAt(right)) {
            count++;
            left--;
            right++;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Every Center

- Try each character as odd-center
- Try each gap as even-center

### 2️⃣ Expand and Count

- Each successful expansion = one palindromic substring
- "aba" at center 'b': expansion 1 = "b", expansion 2 = "aba"

### 3️⃣ Sum All

- Total count = sum of all palindromes from all centers
- Each expansion step discovers exactly one new palindrome

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n²)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I expand around each center -every successful expansion IS a palindromic substring, so I just count all expansions. O(n²) time.'

## 🏆 Length-Prefix Encoding Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String encode(List<String> strs) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (String s : strs) {
            sb.append(s.length()).append('#').append(s);
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }

    public List<String> decode(String s) {
        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
        int i = 0;
        while (i < s.length()) {
            int j = i;
            while (s.charAt(j) != '#') j++;
            int len = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(i, j));
            result.add(s.substring(j + 1, j + 1 + len));
            i = j + 1 + len;
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Encode: Prefix with Length

- Format: `length#string`
- Example: ["hello","world"] → "5#hello5#world"

### 2️⃣ Delimiter Choice

- '#' alone won't work (could appear in strings)
- But length prefix makes it unambiguous
- We know exactly how many chars follow the '#'

### 3️⃣ Decode: Parse Length First

- Read digits until '#' → that's the length
- Read exactly `len` chars after '#' → that's the string
- Jump `i` to next encoded segment

### 4️⃣ Handles Edge Cases

- Empty strings: "0#" → perfectly valid
- Strings containing '#': length tells us where string ends

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n) total characters
- Space: O(1) extra besides output

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use length-prefix encoding: each string is stored as length + # + content -the length makes parsing unambiguous regardless of string content.'

## 🏆 Sliding Window + Two HashMaps

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String minWindow(String s, String t) {
        Map<Character, Integer> need = new HashMap<>();
        for (char c : t.toCharArray()) need.merge(c, 1, Integer::sum);

        int left = 0, minStart = 0, minLen = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int have = 0, required = need.size();
        Map<Character, Integer> window = new HashMap<>();

        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            char c = s.charAt(right);
            window.merge(c, 1, Integer::sum);
            if (need.containsKey(c) && window.get(c).equals(need.get(c))) have++;

            while (have == required) {
                if (right - left + 1 < minLen) {
                    minLen = right - left + 1;
                    minStart = left;
                }
                char leftChar = s.charAt(left);
                window.merge(leftChar, -1, Integer::sum);
                if (need.containsKey(leftChar) && window.get(leftChar) < need.get(leftChar)) have--;
                left++;
            }
        }
        return minLen == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? "" : s.substring(minStart, minStart + minLen);
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Build Requirement Map

- `need` map stores required frequency for each char in t
- `required` = number of unique chars to satisfy

### 2️⃣ Expand Right to Satisfy

- Add chars to window map
- When a char's count matches its requirement → increment `have`

### 3️⃣ Shrink Left to Minimize

- Once `have == required` → window is valid
- Try removing from left to find smaller valid window
- If removing breaks a requirement → decrement `have`

### 4️⃣ Track Minimum

- Update minStart and minLen whenever valid window is smaller
- Final answer uses these to extract substring

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(|s| + |t|)
- Space: O(|s| + |t|)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I use a sliding window -expand right until all of t is covered, then shrink left to minimize -tracking how many characters satisfy their required count.'

## 🏆 Backtracking Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public List<String> generateParenthesis(int n) {
        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
        backtrack(result, new StringBuilder(), 0, 0, n);
        return result;
    }

    private void backtrack(List<String> result, StringBuilder sb, int open, int close, int n) {
        if (sb.length() == 2 * n) {
            result.add(sb.toString());
            return;
        }
        if (open < n) {
            sb.append('(');
            backtrack(result, sb, open + 1, close, n);
            sb.deleteCharAt(sb.length() - 1);
        }
        if (close < open) {
            sb.append(')');
            backtrack(result, sb, open, close + 1, n);
            sb.deleteCharAt(sb.length() - 1);
        }
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Track Open and Close Counts

- `open` = number of '(' used so far
- `close` = number of ')' used so far

### 2️⃣ Rule 1: Add Open

- Can add '(' if `open < n`
- Haven't used all n opening brackets yet

### 3️⃣ Rule 2: Add Close

- Can add ')' only if `close < open`
- Ensures we never have more ')' than '(' at any point
- This guarantees validity

### 4️⃣ Base Case

- String length == 2n → complete valid combination
- Add to result

### 5️⃣ Backtrack

- Delete last char after recursive call
- Explores all valid paths

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(4^n / √n) -nth Catalan number
- Space: O(n) recursion depth

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I backtrack with two simple rules -add open if count < n, add close if count < open -this naturally generates only valid combinations.'

## 🏆 Character Frequency Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int longestPalindrome(String s) {
        int[] count = new int[128];
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) count[c]++;
        int oddCount = 0;
        for (int c : count) {
            if (c % 2 != 0) oddCount++;
        }
        return s.length() - oddCount + (oddCount > 0 ? 1 : 0);
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Count All Characters

- `int[128]` handles both upper and lowercase
- Count frequency of each character

### 2️⃣ Count Odd Frequencies

- Characters with odd count can only contribute (count-1) to palindrome
- Unless placed in the center

### 3️⃣ Calculate Length

- `total - oddCount` = all paired characters used
- `+ 1` if any odd char exists (one goes in center)

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1) -fixed 128 ASCII

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I count characters with odd frequency -subtract them all from total length, add back 1 for the center if any odd exists.'

## 🏆 Fixed Sliding Window Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        if (s.length() < p.length()) return result;
        int[] pCount = new int[26], sCount = new int[26];
        for (int i = 0; i < p.length(); i++) {
            pCount[p.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            sCount[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
        }
        if (Arrays.equals(pCount, sCount)) result.add(0);
        for (int i = p.length(); i < s.length(); i++) {
            sCount[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            sCount[s.charAt(i - p.length()) - 'a']--;
            if (Arrays.equals(pCount, sCount)) result.add(i - p.length() + 1);
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Build Target Frequency

- `pCount` = frequency of each char in pattern p
- This is what we're looking for in every window

### 2️⃣ Initialize First Window

- Build `sCount` for first window of size len(p)
- Check if first window is an anagram

### 3️⃣ Slide One Character at a Time

- Add new right character to window
- Remove old left character from window
- O(1) per slide

### 4️⃣ Compare at Each Position

- If `sCount` equals `pCount` → anagram found
- Record start index

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n) -comparing 26-element arrays is O(1)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I slide a fixed window of size len(p) across s, maintaining a frequency array -if it matches p's frequency array, that's an anagram.'

## 🏆 Sequential Parsing Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int myAtoi(String s) {
        int i = 0, n = s.length(), sign = 1;
        long result = 0;
        while (i < n && s.charAt(i) == ' ') i++;
        if (i < n && (s.charAt(i) == '+' || s.charAt(i) == '-')) {
            sign = s.charAt(i) == '-' ? -1 : 1;
            i++;
        }
        while (i < n && Character.isDigit(s.charAt(i))) {
            result = result * 10 + (s.charAt(i) - '0');
            if (result * sign > Integer.MAX_VALUE) return Integer.MAX_VALUE;
            if (result * sign < Integer.MIN_VALUE) return Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            i++;
        }
        return (int)(result * sign);
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Skip Leading Whitespace

- Move `i` past all spaces
- Only leading spaces are ignored

### 2️⃣ Detect Sign

- Check for '+' or '-'
- Default sign = +1
- Only ONE sign character allowed

### 3️⃣ Read Consecutive Digits

- Build number: `result = result * 10 + digit`
- Stop at first non-digit character

### 4️⃣ Clamp on Overflow

- Check after each digit if result exceeds INT range
- Return MAX_VALUE or MIN_VALUE accordingly

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I parse sequentially: skip spaces, detect sign, accumulate digits, and clamp to INT_MIN/MAX on overflow -strict left-to-right processing.'

## 🏆 Split and Reverse Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String reverseWords(String s) {
        String[] words = s.trim().split("\\s+");
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = words.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            sb.append(words[i]);
            if (i > 0) sb.append(' ');
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Trim

- Remove leading and trailing spaces
- Clean up input

### 2️⃣ Split by Whitespace

- `\\s+` splits by one or more spaces
- Handles multiple consecutive spaces

### 3️⃣ Reverse Iteration

- Loop from last word to first
- Append each word with single space between

### 4️⃣ Build Result

- StringBuilder efficiently concatenates
- No trailing space needed

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(n)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I trim, split by whitespace regex, iterate words in reverse, and join with single spaces. For O(1) space: reverse entire string, then reverse each word.'

## 🏆 Compare Adjacent Values Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int romanToInt(String s) {
        Map<Character, Integer> map = Map.of(
            'I', 1, 'V', 5, 'X', 10, 'L', 50,
            'C', 100, 'D', 500, 'M', 1000
        );
        int result = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            if (i + 1 < s.length() && map.get(s.charAt(i)) < map.get(s.charAt(i + 1))) {
                result -= map.get(s.charAt(i));
            } else {
                result += map.get(s.charAt(i));
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Value Map

- Map each Roman numeral char to its integer value
- I=1, V=5, X=10, L=50, C=100, D=500, M=1000

### 2️⃣ Compare Current with Next

- If current < next → subtraction case (e.g., IV = 4, IX = 9)
- Otherwise → addition case (normal)

### 3️⃣ Accumulate Result

- Subtract when smaller precedes larger
- Add otherwise
- Single pass left-to-right

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n)
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I iterate left-to-right -if current value is less than next, subtract it; otherwise add it. Handles all cases like IV, IX, XL naturally.'

## 🏆 Horizontal Scan Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String longestCommonPrefix(String[] strs) {
        if (strs.length == 0) return "";
        String prefix = strs[0];
        for (int i = 1; i < strs.length; i++) {
            while (strs[i].indexOf(prefix) != 0) {
                prefix = prefix.substring(0, prefix.length() - 1);
                if (prefix.isEmpty()) return "";
            }
        }
        return prefix;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Start with First String

- Use entire first string as initial prefix candidate
- It's the maximum possible prefix

### 2️⃣ Shrink Against Each String

- Check if prefix is a prefix of current string
- If not → remove last character and retry

### 3️⃣ Early Termination

- If prefix becomes empty → no common prefix exists
- Return immediately

### 4️⃣ Survives All Strings

- Whatever remains after checking all strings = longest common prefix

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(S) where S = sum of all characters
- Space: O(1)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I start with the first string as prefix, then iteratively shrink it from the end until it's a prefix of every other string.'

## 🏆 Iterative Build Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public String countAndSay(int n) {
        String result = "1";
        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
            int count = 1;
            for (int j = 1; j < result.length(); j++) {
                if (result.charAt(j) == result.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    count++;
                } else {
                    sb.append(count).append(result.charAt(j - 1));
                    count = 1;
                }
            }
            sb.append(count).append(result.charAt(result.length() - 1));
            result = sb.toString();
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Base Case

- Start with "1"
- Build each subsequent term from previous

### 2️⃣ Count Consecutive Characters

- Compare each char with previous
- Same → increment count
- Different → emit "count + char", reset count

### 3️⃣ Emit Last Group

