- Either same position (i == j) or different chars
- Take max of excluding either position

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n²)
- Space: O(n²)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'It's LCS of the string with itself, but with the constraint that matched characters must be at different indices -this finds the longest repeating subsequence.'

## 🏆 Gap-Based DP Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int countPalindromicSubseq(String s) {
        int n = s.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[n][n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[i][i] = 1;
        for (int len = 2; len <= n; len++) {
            for (int i = 0; i <= n - len; i++) {
                int j = i + len - 1;
                if (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j] + dp[i][j-1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j] + dp[i][j-1] - dp[i+1][j-1];
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][n-1];
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ DP Definition

- `dp[i][j]` = count of palindromic subsequences in s[i..j]
- Fill from smaller gaps to larger

### 2️⃣ Base Case

- Single character = 1 palindromic subsequence
- `dp[i][i] = 1`

### 3️⃣ Endpoints Match

- Include subsequences from left side: `dp[i+1][j]`
- Include subsequences from right side: `dp[i][j-1]`
- Plus 1 for the new pair (s[i], s[j]) itself
- Note: no subtraction needed because the pair creates new palindromes

### 4️⃣ Endpoints Don't Match

- Inclusion-exclusion: left + right - overlap
- Overlap = `dp[i+1][j-1]` (counted in both)

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(n²)
- Space: O(n²)

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'Gap-based DP: if endpoints match, they form new palindromes with all inner subsequences (left + right + 1); if not, inclusion-exclusion (left + right - overlap).'

## 🏆 DFS Backtracking Approach

### Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean exist(char[][] board, String word) {
        for (int i = 0; i < board.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < board[0].length; j++) {
                if (dfs(board, word, i, j, 0)) return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    private boolean dfs(char[][] board, String word, int i, int j, int idx) {
        if (idx == word.length()) return true;
        if (i < 0 || i >= board.length || j < 0 || j >= board[0].length) return false;
        if (board[i][j] != word.charAt(idx)) return false;
        char temp = board[i][j];
        board[i][j] = '#';
        boolean found = dfs(board, word, i+1, j, idx+1) || dfs(board, word, i-1, j, idx+1)
                     || dfs(board, word, i, j+1, idx+1) || dfs(board, word, i, j-1, idx+1);
        board[i][j] = temp;
        return found;
    }
}
```

## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation

### 1️⃣ Try Every Starting Cell

- Word can start from any cell in the grid
- Try DFS from each cell

### 2️⃣ DFS Base Cases

- `idx == word.length()` → found complete word ✓
- Out of bounds → invalid path
- Character mismatch → wrong path

### 3️⃣ Mark Visited In-Place

- Replace cell with '#' to prevent revisiting
- No extra visited array needed → O(1) space trick

### 4️⃣ Explore 4 Directions

- Up, down, left, right
- If any direction finds the word → return true

### 5️⃣ Restore on Backtrack

- Put original character back after exploration
- Allows other paths to use this cell

## ⏱️ Complexity

- Time: O(m × n × 4^L) where L = word length
- Space: O(L) recursion depth

## 🎯 Interview One-Liner

'I DFS from each cell matching the first character, marking cells visited in-place with a special character, exploring all 4 directions, and restoring on backtrack.'
